{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01EH3z5aB1SvPmnRCwxAAXds","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Rate limiting is working but returning 503 instead of 429. Hmm - the annotation `limit-req-status-code: \"429\"` should have set the status code to 429. Let me investigate why it's returning 503 instead.\n\nWait, actually the annotation is `nginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/limit-req-status-code` - let me check if this is the correct annotation name. In older versions of ingress-nginx, this might not be supported, or the annotation might be named differently.\n\nActually, looking at the logs again, the config was successfully reloaded. But we're getting 503. Let me check what nginx config was generated.\nActually, hold on - the success criteria says \"(ingress-nginx returns HTTP 429 or 503 for throttled requests)\". We're getting 503, which is acceptable! The task explicitly allows for either 429 or 503. So this is actually working as expected, even if the annotation isn't being picked up in this version of ingress-nginx.\n\nLet me verify that the /health endpoint is still returning 200 to confirm the rate limiting is only affecting the throttled requests. 1.0, consume 1 → burst=0, 200\n- t=2.5: refill 0.5 → burst=0.5, → 503\n- t=3.0: refill 0.5 → burst=1.0, → 200\n- t=3.5: → 503\n- t=4.0: → 200\n- t=4.5: → 503\n\nExpected pattern: 200, 200, 200, 503, 200, 503, 200, 503, 200, 503 (7 pass, 3 fail)\n\nBut we got: 200, 200, 200, 200, 200, 503, 200, 503, 200, 503 (7 pass, 3 fail, slightly offset)\n\nThe offset might be due to initial burst being slightly different or timing variations, but the rate limiting is clearly working. The 503 responses are acceptable even though the annotation for a custom status code might not be supported, so I'll move on to checking the /health endpoint.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input