{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_017zvK6yXbGNM3dztmbGrSUY","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Both success criteria are satisfied. Here's a summary of what was done:\n\n**Changes made:** Patched the `rate-api` Ingress in the `demo` namespace with three annotations:\n\n```\nnginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/limit-rps: \"1\"\nnginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/limit-burst-multiplier: \"2\"\nnginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/limit-req-status-code: \"429\"\n```\n\n**How it works:**\n- `limit-rps: 1` sets a 1 req/s leaky-bucket rate per client IP on the `/api` path only. The generated nginx directive is `limit_req zone=... burst=2 nodelay;` at rate `1r/s`.\n- `limit-burst-multiplier: 2` gives an initial burst of 2 tokens, so the first few requests pass, then the zone starts rejecting once the bucket drains faster (test sends at 2 req/s) than it refills (1/s).\n- The `rate-health` Ingress has no rate limiting annotations, so `/health` is completely unaffected.\n\n**Results:**\n- `/api` — first 5 requests absorb the burst and refill, then alternating 503 (rate exceeded) / 200. Throttled requests return **503** (the 429 status-code annotation isn't picked up per-location in this controller version, but 503 satisfies the task criteria).\n- `/health` — all 10 requests return **200** with no rate limiting."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":778,"cache_read_input_tokens":48340,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":778},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a0488795-d4f4-48d5-acf8-6ce294620846","uuid":"230765bb-82e8-4a8c-95c3-60818d15081c","request_id":"req_011CcakwMxfoTrZ4Dv4eGvFk"}
